<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_5:_2.3_A_Numerical_Example:_Cooks_in_the_Kitchen">Notes for Week 5: 2.3 A Numerical Example: Cooks in the Kitchen</span></h2>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="The_Production_Function">The Production Function</span></h1>
<p>To present the <em><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Production_function">Production Function</a></em> a model for Black Dog restaurant is presented. Using first the following table:</p>
<table border="1">
  <tr>
    <td># of Cooks</td>
    <td># of Sandwiches</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>0</td>
    <td>0</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>1</td>
    <td>40</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>2</td>
    <td>90</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>3</td>
    <td>120</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>4</td>
    <td>135</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>5</td>
    <td>140</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>6</td>
    <td>142</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>The curve resulting in plotting this function is the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Production_function">Production Function</a>: the relationship between quantity of inputs used to make a good and the quantity of output of that good.</p>
<p>The <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_product">Marginal product of labor</a> (MPL) as the slope of the  <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Production_function">Production Function</a> is illustrated. The MPL is the increase in output
that arises from an additional unit of input, but as the number of workers increases, the MPL declines. When the MPL is plotted an U-inverted curve is presented.</p>
<p>An updated table including a column for the marginal product is presented as:</p>
<table border="1">
  <tr>
    <td># of Cooks</td>
    <td># of Sandwiches</td>
    <td>Marginal Product</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>0</td>
    <td>0</td>
    <td>0</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>1</td>
    <td>40</td>
    <td>40</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>2</td>
    <td>90</td>
    <td>50</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>3</td>
    <td>120</td>
    <td>30</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>4</td>
    <td>135</td>
    <td>15</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>5</td>
    <td>140</td>
    <td>5</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>6</td>
    <td>142</td>
    <td>2</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>The equation for the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_product">Marginal Product</a> is:
$$MP = \Delta Q / \Delta L$$</p>
<p>As an example for the calculation of the MP for 3 Cooks:
$$MP&#95;3 = \Delta Q&#95;3 / \Delta L&#95;3 = (Q&#95;3 - Q&#95;2)/(L&#95;3 - L&#95;2) = (120 - 90)/(3-2)= 30/1=30$$</p>
<p>The output of this hypothetical example illustrates the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diminishing_returns">Diminishing Marginal Product</a>: the property whereby the <em>marginal product</em> of an input <strong>declines</strong> as the <em>quantity</em> of the input <strong>increases</strong>.</p>

